# Format Markdown for readability and clean diffs

Apply when creating or editing Markdown (READMEs, docs, RFCs, ADRs, release notes).

## Structure

- One **H1** per file at the top; use `##` and `###` for sections—don't skip levels.
- Short paragraphs (1–4 sentences). Prefer bullets for enumerations.
- Add a TOC only when the file has roughly 5+ top-level sections.

## Headings and lists

- **Sentence case** for headings (`## Getting started`).
- Use `-` for unordered lists; indent nested items by **2 spaces**.
- Numbered lists only when order matters.

## Code, links, emphasis

- Always use **fenced code blocks** with a language tag (` ```ts `, ` ```bash `, ` ```json `).
- Inline code with backticks for filenames, commands, identifiers (`package.json`, `npm test`, `UserService`).
- Links: `[descriptive text](https://example.com)`. No bare URLs, no "click here".
- `**bold**` for key terms, `*italics*` sparingly. No ALL CAPS.

## Tables

```markdown
| Field | Type   | Notes              |
|-------|--------|--------------------|
| id    | string | UUID v4            |
| email | string | Lowercased on save |
```

Keep tables narrow; for wide content, prefer lists.

## Hygiene

- One sentence per line **or** wrap at ~100 cols—be consistent within a file.
- Blank line before and after headings, lists, code fences, tables.
- End with a single newline; no trailing whitespace.
- Relative links for in-repo files (`./CONTRIBUTING.md`); absolute URLs for external.

## README minimum

1. Title and one-line summary
2. Quickstart (install + run)
3. Usage example
4. Configuration / environment
5. Scripts or commands
6. Contributing / license pointers
